Saralin belched out a flame, igniting a small patch of forest and then circling above it, observing the situation. Strangely, when he slowed down, the eerie screams trailing behind him also ceased. Saralin forgot that there was a passenger on his back.
"Please, Tenuk, you've shifted into a Slacker before!"
"It's a different story to fly on my own and suddenly get dragged away by a huge pink dragon!"
"Is Kayel still okay?"
Kayel clearly disagreed with Nix's statement; he looked paler than usual, and his claws had dug deep into Saralin's back, drawing blood from the Slackers, but Saralin didn't seem to mind. Still, Saralin realized he had scared his new friend and thus landed in an open area.
"Sorry sorry, I caught a scent. I need to deal with it!"
"Do you have to drag us along too?" Tenuk slid down from Saralin's back, following his tail to the ground, and asked with a sharp tone. "We left Revtvik behind! We abandoned that strong and brawny giant! How will he find us?"
"...He'll find a way..." Nix said with a click of his tongue. "Revtvik may be slow, but he's not stupid."
"Can Revtvik drive?"
Nix blinked, turning to look at Tenuk. "Of course he can drive."
"Have you ever seen Revtvik drive? He doesn't have a truck like yours, and I've never seen him drive a cute little car like Kayel. He started riding the bus to work just because you always drove us to work. He only has a bicycle."
A burst of laughter interrupted them. Saralin suddenly laughed uncontrollably, but no one knew what he was laughing at. It took Saralin a while to calm down.
"Sorry sorry, I just imagined my big armored friend riding a cute little bicycle specially designed for Tumson children. That's too funny! I wish I had telepathy. This idea is too interesting! I must treasure it!"
Kayel also laughed, imagining what Saralin was thinking. "Okay, okay. But what did you smell? Why fly so fast?"
Saralin grunted, took off, and quickly disappeared before returning with a corpse in front of Nix. It was an Oroslak, a very rare golden-white dragon species. But its head was gone. "Another one dead. I heard their cries. Smelled their blood. I must protect them, hunt the killers. This is Isini's will. Those creatures are nearby."
The powerful Slacker suddenly stiffened. Nix and Kayel also stiffened, their attention drawn to a gap at the edge of the clearing. A huge and black entity stared at them, hissing. It suddenly spread its two pairs of enormous wings and charged forward, its target straight at Saralin, paying no mind to the three small ones in its way. Kayel and Tenuk barely managed to dodge to the side, but Nix found himself dragged to the ground, nearly thrown onto Saralin's back.
Saralin grabbed Nix with its long and dexterous tail, tossing her onto its back, and then took off. The black entity with two pairs of wings quickly caught up.
Kayel clicked his tongue, drew a rifle from behind, opened a bag, and took out a belt of ammunition. He hung the belt in front of him for easy access, but soon realized that Nix, Saralin, and the monster were nowhere to be seen.
"Hey, Tenuk, could you transform into a flying creature?" Kayel asked.
"Do you want to go after them?"
"Trash talk."
"But... one of them is a giant monster!"
"Then what? This rifle in my hands has powerful firepower and can fire at any time. I just need to see it to bring it down."
Tenuk hesitated for a moment, then took a step back to give himself some space. With a low, slightly painful groan, Tenuk's body stretched out, his fur turning into scales, and his arms transforming into wings. He quickly turned into an ordinary light blue Slacker, but his eyes remained red.
"Climb on."
Tenuk now looked like an ordinary Slacker, with neatly arranged scales on his back and a pair of spines to help Kayel grab onto him. It took Tenuk a long time to take off, but once airborne, he quickly adjusted his direction and made a determined effort to catch up.
However, Tenuk and Kayel soon realized they weren't facing just one opponent. A second dark creature emerged from beneath them, and Tenuk barely dodged the collision.
"Is this the terrifying large monster Lanekes was worried about?" Kayel frowned, trying to shoot at the second monster but missing, and quickly reloaded.
Tenuk didn't respond; he was busy flying towards Nix and Saralin, even though another monster was chasing them. Kayel clumsily turned around to face the monster. The monster was pursuing them, and Kayel thought this was good news because it would be easier to aim and shoot. Two bullets pierced the monster's upper wing, and it let out a painful roar before disappearing into the forest. Kayel wasn't sure if it was still following them, but he felt it wouldn't be able to keep up.
In front, Saralin was wildly swinging his body, spraying flames at the black monster, while Nix desperately clung to Saralin to avoid falling. Although the monster was certainly injured, it seemed enraged and unwilling to retreat, and the fireballs didn't seem to cause much damage. After stabilizing his body, Nix took the opportunity to pull out her weapon, a shotgun she trusted. Of course, a shotgun couldn't handle such a monster, but the scattered bullets might at least scare off this black beast?
